data.content:
Build succeeds. Here's the full summary of **all EF Core 9 breaking changes** affecting this app:

---

### ✅ Fixed in this project

**1. TFM & packages** — `net8.0` → `net9.0`, packages `8.0.0` → `9.0.0`

**2. `Migrate()` inside user transaction** (`MigrationRunner.cs`)
EF Core 9 throws `InvalidOperationException` if `Migrate()` is called inside a `BeginTransaction()` block. Migrations now manage their own transactions internally. **Fix:** removed the wrapping `BeginTransaction`/`Commit`.

---

### ⚠️ Required fixes in your Cosmos DB project

**3. Discriminator property renamed from `"Discriminator"` → `"$type"`**
EF Core 9's Cosmos provider changed the default discriminator property name. Existing documents still store `"Discriminator"`, so queries will fail silently or return no results. **Fix** — in your Cosmos `DbContext.OnModelCreating`, pin the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<YourEntity>().HasDiscriminator<string>("Discriminator");
// Or globally for all entities:
foreach (var entityType in modelBuilder.Model.GetEntityTypes())
{
    entityType.SetDiscriminatorProperty(
        entityType.FindProperty("Discriminator")
        ?? entityType.AddProperty("Discriminator", typeof(string)));
}
```

**4. Synchronous Cosmos DB I/O now throws**
EF Core 9 removed sync-over-async support for the Cosmos provider. Any call like `.ToList()`, `.First()`, `.Single()`, `.Count()`, etc. will throw `InvalidOperationException`. **Fix** — convert all queries to async:

```csharp
// Before (throws in EF Core 9):
var items = cosmosDb.Products.Where(p => p.Active).ToList();
var first = cosmosDb.Products.First(p => p.Id == id);

// After:
var items = await cosmosDb.Products.Where(p => p.Active).ToListAsync();
var first = await cosmosDb.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
```

This also applies to `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()` on the Cosmos provider.
